{
  "texts": [
    "The development of mobile technology has led to the gradual popularization of social software such as WeChat, where communication between patients and physicians can be shifted from offline to online, in addition, the World Health Organization has called for the expansion of the use of digital technology to improve health support for patients, which have effectively contributed to the development of mobile health (mHealth) (24) (25) (26) (27) (28).",
    "As a result, mHealth is widely used by a large number of healthcare entities and plays an important role in the prevention and treatment of chronic diseases such as hypertension, diabetes, asthma, and postoperative rehabilitation of the heart and lungs and can save up to seven billion dollars in budgets annually (29, 30).",
    "The use of cell phones and mHealth apps continues to proliferate, with an increasing number of healthcare professionals, young and highly educated patients, and the general public using health apps (31) (32) (33) (34).",
    "Evidence suggests that the use of mHealth apps can play an important role in patient education, disease self-management, remote monitoring of patients, and improvement of quality of life (35) (36) (37).",
    "For example, LianHong Wang et al."
  ]
}